Intuitively, we may presume that vectors $	extbf{\em u}$ and $\mathbf{
abla}w$ are directionally aligned, given that ${\pmb u}^{T}{\pmb w}>0$ . In this scenario, align $>0$ implies that vector $\pmb{v}$ is drawing $	extbf{\em u}$ closer towards the reference vector $\pmb{w}$ . Conversely, vector $\pmb{v}$ is propelling $	extbf{\em u}$ away from $\pmb{w}$ . Similar arguments hold for $a l i g n<0$ : $\pmb{v}$ pushes $	extbf{\em u}$ away from the reference vector $\mathbf{
abla}w$ when $	extbf{\em u}$ and $\pmb{w}$ share the same directional orientation. Conversely, $\pmb{v}$ pulls $	extbf{\em u}$ towards the reference vector $\mathbf{
abla}w$ when the vectors $	extbf{\em u}$ and $\mathbf{
abla}w$ are not oriented in the same direction.

